---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout>
	<main class="min-h-dvh bg-black text-white px-[5%] py-8 flex items-center justify-center">
		<div class="max-w-2xl mx-auto w-full">
			<h1 class="text-2xl font-mono mb-16 text-center">FAQ</h1>
			
			<div class="space-y-6">
				<!-- What a Sigil Is -->
				<div class="accordion-item">
					<button 
						class="accordion-button w-full text-left py-4 px-4 bg-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors flex items-center"
						aria-expanded="false"
						aria-controls="content-1"
					>
						<span class="text-gray-500 text-xs sm:text-sm leading-tight uppercase flex-1">What a Sigil Is</span>
					</button>
					<div 
						id="content-1" 
						class="accordion-content hidden overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300"
						aria-hidden="true"
					>
						<div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-2 text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
							<p class="mb-3">
								A sigil is a symbolic representation of an intention.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								It converts a verbal desire into a visual form.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								The purpose is compression: language becomes symbol, symbol becomes focus.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								Once the sigil exists, the original sentence is no longer relevant. The visual mark becomes the container for the meaning.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Why Sigils Are Used -->
				<div class="accordion-item">
					<button 
						class="accordion-button w-full text-left py-4 px-4 bg-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors flex items-center"
						aria-expanded="false"
						aria-controls="content-2"
					>
						<span class="text-gray-500 text-xs sm:text-sm leading-tight uppercase flex-1">Why Sigils Are Used</span>
					</button>
					<div 
						id="content-2" 
						class="accordion-content hidden overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300"
						aria-hidden="true"
					>
						<div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-2 text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
							<p class="mb-3">
								Written language occupies the analytical mind.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								Symbolic forms bypass it.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								A sigil is meant to be interacted with until the conscious narrative dissolves and the intent persists without words.
							</p>
							<p>
								The effect depends on attention, repetition, and the internal state of the operator — not belief, petition, or theatrics.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- How To Use a Sigil -->
				<div class="accordion-item">
					<button 
						class="accordion-button w-full text-left py-4 px-4 bg-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors flex items-center"
						aria-expanded="false"
						aria-controls="content-3"
					>
						<span class="text-gray-500 text-xs sm:text-sm leading-tight uppercase flex-1">How To Use a Sigil</span>
					</button>
					<div 
						id="content-3" 
						class="accordion-content hidden overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300"
						aria-hidden="true"
					>
						<div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-2 text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
							<p class="mb-4 font-semibold">Define the intention.</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								Phrase it clearly and privately. You don't show it to anyone. You don't justify it.
							</p>

							<p class="mb-4 font-semibold">Generate the sigil.</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								The system converts the request into a visual mark. The text is discarded.
							</p>

							<p class="mb-4 font-semibold">Focus.</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								Look at the sigil until it stops being a drawing and becomes a shape you recognize without thinking.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								When it becomes familiar, it has taken root.
							</p>

							<p class="mb-4 font-semibold">Charge.</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								Use a moment of heightened physical, emotional, or psychological energy.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								Arousal, fear, exhaustion, trance, silence — the type doesn't matter.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								The point is intensity and non-verbal focus.
							</p>

							<p class="mb-4 font-semibold">Release.</p>
							<p class="mb-4">
								Stop thinking about it.
							</p>
							<p>
								You don't revisit the intention. You don't question outcomes.
							</p>
							<p>
								The sigil remains active without attention.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- How This Sigil Engine Functions -->
				<div class="accordion-item">
					<button 
						class="accordion-button w-full text-left py-4 px-4 bg-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors flex items-center"
						aria-expanded="false"
						aria-controls="content-6"
					>
						<span class="text-gray-500 text-xs sm:text-sm leading-tight uppercase flex-1">How This Sigil Engine Functions</span>
					</button>
					<div 
						id="content-6" 
						class="accordion-content hidden overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300"
						aria-hidden="true"
					>
						<div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-2 text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
							<p class="mb-3">
								These sigils aren't meant to be interpreted.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								They aren't symbolic in the traditional sense, and don't reference letters, runes, or iconography.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								It's a compressed instruction set.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								The lines represent pathways.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								The nodes represent decision points.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								The overall structure represents a condition placed into motion.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								To use it, you don't analyze it.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								You engage with it until it becomes familiar enough that you recognize it instantly, without having to think.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								That familiarity is the point.
							</p>
							<p>
								Once the form is internalized, the original intention remains active independent of language.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- Ritual Use with Clauneck -->
				<div class="accordion-item">
					<button 
						class="accordion-button w-full text-left py-4 px-4 bg-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors flex items-center"
						aria-expanded="false"
						aria-controls="content-4"
					>
						<span class="text-gray-500 text-xs sm:text-sm leading-tight uppercase flex-1">Ritual Use with Clauneck</span>
					</button>
					<div 
						id="content-4" 
						class="accordion-content hidden overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300"
						aria-hidden="true"
					>
						<div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-2 text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
							<p class="mb-3">
								If used alongside a Clauneck working, the sigil functions as the personal vector of the operator's intention, separate from the entity itself.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								Clauneck is invoked or acknowledged — the sigil is the payload.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								You do not combine them visually. You do not redesign the sigil.
							</p>
							<p>
								The entity is the channel. The sigil is the instruction.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>

				<!-- After Use -->
				<div class="accordion-item">
					<button 
						class="accordion-button w-full text-left py-4 px-4 bg-gray-900 hover:bg-gray-800 transition-colors flex items-center"
						aria-expanded="false"
						aria-controls="content-5"
					>
						<span class="text-gray-500 text-xs sm:text-sm leading-tight uppercase flex-1">After Use</span>
					</button>
					<div 
						id="content-5" 
						class="accordion-content hidden overflow-hidden transition-all duration-300"
						aria-hidden="true"
					>
						<div class="px-4 pb-4 pt-2 text-sm text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
							<p class="mb-3">
								Destroying the physical sigil is optional.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								Some burn it.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								Some hide it.
							</p>
							<p class="mb-3">
								Some keep it in plain sight where only they recognize it.
							</p>
							<p>
								Meaning is decided by strain, duration, and repetition — not aesthetics.
							</p>
						</div>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>

			<div class="mt-16 text-center">
				<a href="/" class="text-gray-500 font-mono text-sm hover:text-green-400 transition-colors underline">
					← BACK
				</a>
			</div>
		</div>
	</main>
</Layout>

<script>
	document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
		const buttons = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-button');
		
		buttons.forEach((button) => {
			button.addEventListener('click', () => {
				const content = button.nextElementSibling as HTMLElement;
				const isExpanded = button.getAttribute('aria-expanded') === 'true';
				
				// Close all other accordions
				buttons.forEach((otherButton) => {
					if (otherButton !== button) {
						const otherContent = otherButton.nextElementSibling as HTMLElement;
						
						otherButton.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
						otherContent.classList.add('hidden');
						otherContent.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'true');
					}
				});
				
				// Toggle current accordion
				if (isExpanded) {
					button.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'false');
					content.classList.add('hidden');
					content.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'true');
				} else {
					button.setAttribute('aria-expanded', 'true');
					content.classList.remove('hidden');
					content.setAttribute('aria-hidden', 'false');
				}
			});
			
			// Keyboard support
			button.addEventListener('keydown', (e) => {
				const keyEvent = e as KeyboardEvent;
				if (keyEvent.key === 'Enter' || keyEvent.key === ' ') {
					keyEvent.preventDefault();
					(button as HTMLElement).click();
				}
			});
		});
	});
</script>

<style>
	.accordion-content {
		max-height: 0;
	}
	
	.accordion-content:not(.hidden) {
		max-height: 2000px;
	}
	
	.accordion-button span.uppercase {
		text-transform: uppercase !important;
	}
</style>

